    // This is still `N-1` recomputations for each `k` that depends on `a_1`.
    // This is `O(N^2)`.

    // The problem is a variation of "path finding on a graph with one changing edge".
    // The graph has N nodes. Each node has out-degree 2 (x+a_x, x-a_x).
    // The `a_x` values are fixed for `x >= 2`. Only `a_1` changes.
    // This is a functional graph (each node has exactly one outgoing edge if we combine steps 2 and 3).
    // `f(x) = (x+a_x) - a_{x+a_x}`.
    // We are looking for `y` sum along the path `x, f(x), f(f(x)), ...`
    // The graph is a collection of components, each consisting of a set of trees leading into a cycle.
    // When `a_1` changes, the edge from `1` changes.
    // This means the component containing `1` changes.
    // Other components are unaffected.
    // So, we can precompute all components not containing `1`.
    // For components containing `1`, we need to re-evaluate.
    // The path from `x` to termination/cycle is `x -> x_1 -> x_2 -> ...`.
    // If `x_k = 1` at any point, then the path depends on `a_1`.
    // If `x_k != 1` for all `k`, then the path does not depend on `a_1`.

    // Let's use the `state_optimized` and `memo_optimized` as defined.
    // The `for (int k = 2; k <= n; ++k)` loop should be outside the `for (int i = 1; i < n; ++i)` loop.
    // This precomputes all paths that *do not* involve `x=1`.
    // If a path from `k` (where `k >= 2`) *does* involve `x=1`, then `std::get<2>(memo_optimized[k])` will be true.
    // In this case, `memo_optimized[k]` is invalid for subsequent `a_1` values.
    // So, when `solve_optimized(..., k)` is called from `solve_optimized(..., 1)`:
    //   If `k != 1` and `state_optimized[k] == 2` and `std::get<2>(memo_optimized[k]) == true`,
    //   then `memo_optimized[k]` is invalid. We must recompute.
    //   To recompute, we need to set `state_optimized[k] = 0`.
    //   This is what the `if (current_x != 1 && std::get<2>(memo_optimized[current_x]))` block does.
    // This means that any state `k` whose path depends on `a_1` will be recomputed *every time* `a_1` changes.
    // This is still `O(N^2)` in the worst case.

    // The only way this is not O(N^2) is if the total number of states `k` for which `depends_on_a1` is true
    // and which are visited by `solve_optimized(..., 1)` is small, or if the recomputation is shallow.
    // The problem constraints strongly suggest O(N) or O(N log N).

    // Let's consider the structure of the graph.
