        //
        // If $n$ is even:
        // This construction is invalid because class sizes are $n$ (even).
        //
        // The problem statement is tricky. It doesn't ask for a specific construction, just the minimum difference.
        // The fact that $a_n - a_{n-1}$ is the answer for all examples strongly suggests it's the general solution.
        //
        // The proof relies on the fact that if you have $2n$ elements, and you partition them into two sets of odd sizes,
        // say $S_1 = 2k_1+1$ and $S_2 = 2k_2+1$, then $k_1+k_2 = n-1$.
        // The median of the first set $M_1$ must be some $a_i$.
        // The median of the second set $M_2$ must be some $a_j$.
        //
        // It can be shown that $M_1 \le a_{n-1}$ and $M_2 \ge a_n$ (or vice versa).
