void solve() {
    int n;
    std::cin >> n;
    long long cost = 0;
    long long current_positive_balance = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        long long val;
        std::cin >> val;
        if (val > 0) {
            current_positive_balance += val;
        } else { // val <= 0
            // We need to move |val| units into this position.
            // These units can come from current_positive_balance (free, i.e., from j < i)
            // or from positions j > i (costly).
            // We prioritize using current_positive_balance as it's free.
            long long units_needed = -val;
            if (current_positive_balance >= units_needed) {
                current_positive_balance -= units_needed;
            } else {
                // Not enough positive balance from left.
                // We use all available current_positive_balance.
                units_needed -= current_positive_balance;
                current_positive_balance = 0;
                // The remaining units_needed must come from positions j > i.
                // Moving units from j > i to i (j > i) is costly.
                // This is equivalent to moving units from i to j < i (i > j)
                // which is also costly.
                // The problem statement says: decrement a_i, increment a_j.
                // If a_i is negative, we need to increment a_i. This means we are j.
                // So we need to find some k such that a_k > 0 and move from k to i.
                // If k < i, it's free. If k > i, it's costly.
                // The current_positive_balance represents sum of a_k > 0 for k < i.
                // If we need more, it means we must take from some a_k > 0 for k > i.
                // This is equivalent to moving a unit from k to i, where k > i.
                // This operation is free.
                // Wait, this is confusing. Let's re-evaluate.
                //
                // The total sum is 0.
                // We want to make all elements 0.
                // Consider the prefix sum `P_k = a_1 + ... + a_k`.
                // If `P_k > 0`, it means we have an excess of `P_k` units that must be moved to indices `j > k`.
                // If `P_k < 0`, it means we have a deficit of `|P_k|` units that must be filled from indices `j > k`.
                //
                // Let's track `balance = a_1 + ... + a_i`.
                // If `balance` becomes negative, say `balance = -X`, it means we need `X` units.
                // These `X` units must come from some `a_j` where `j > i`.
                // To move `X` units from `a_j` (where `j > i`) to `a_i` (where `i < j`), this is a free operation.
                // So, if `balance` becomes negative, we don't incur cost.
                //
                // If `balance` becomes positive, say `balance = +Y`, it means we have `Y` excess units.
                // These `Y` units must be moved to some `a_j` where `j > i`.
                // To move `Y` units from `a_i` to `a_j` (where `i < j`), this is a free operation.
                // So, if `balance` becomes positive, we don't incur cost.
                //
                // The only time we incur cost is when we move a unit from `a_i` to `a_j` where `i > j`.
                // This means `a_i` was positive, and we moved its value to some `a_j` that was negative and `j < i`.
                //
                // Let's maintain `current_sum = a_1 + ... + a_i`.
                // If `current_sum` is positive, it means we have `current_sum` units that need to be moved to the right.
                // These moves are free.
                // If `current_sum` is negative, it means we need `|current_sum|` units from the right.
                // These moves are also free (from right to left).
                //
                // This logic seems to imply 0 cost always, which is incorrect based on examples.
                //
                // The key is that we want to make *all* elements 0.
                // Consider the total amount of positive values that need to be "moved out" to the right.
                // Let `P` be the sum of all `a_k > 0`.
                // Let `N` be the sum of all `a_k < 0`.
                // Since `sum(a_k) = 0`, we have `P + N = 0`, so `P = -N`.
                //
                // We can think of this as a flow problem.
                // We have `a_i` units at index `i`. If `a_i > 0`, it's a source. If `a_i < 0`, it's a sink.
                // We want to move `a_i` units from `i` to `j`.
                //
                // Let's re-read the operation carefully:
                // decrement `a_i` by one, increment `a_j` by one.
                // If `i < j`, free.
                // If `i > j`, cost 1.
                //
                // This means we want to move positive values from left to right as much as possible.
                // And we want to move negative values from right to left as much as possible.
                //
                // Let `balance` be the running sum `a_1 + ... + a_k`.
                // If `a_k` is positive, it contributes to `balance`. This `a_k` needs to be moved out.
                // If `a_k` is negative, it needs to receive value.
                //
                // Consider the prefix sum `S_k = a_1 + ... + a_k`.
                // If `S_k > 0`, it means that up to index `k`, we have an excess of `S_k` units.
                // These `S_k` units must eventually be moved to some `j > k`.
                // Moving from `i <= k` to `j > k` is free.
                // So, `S_k` units can be moved to the right for free.
                //
                // If `S_k < 0`, it means that up to index `k`, we have a deficit of `|S_k|` units.
                // These `|S_k|` units must eventually come from some `j > k`.
                // Moving from `j > k` to `i <= k` is free.
                // So, `|S_k|` units can be received from the right for free.
                //
                // This still implies 0 cost. What am I missing?
                // The crucial part is that we are making `a_i` zero.
                //
                // Let's trace the first example: `a = [-3, 5, -3, 1]`
                // `i=0, a_0 = -3`. `current_positive_balance = 0`. `val = -3`.
                //   `units_needed = 3`. `current_positive_balance` (0) < `units_needed` (3).
                //   `units_needed` becomes `3 - 0 = 3`. `current_positive_balance` becomes 0.
                //   `cost += units_needed` (3). `cost = 3`.
                //   This means we need 3 units for `a_0`. We don't have them from left.
                //   So these 3 units must come from `a_j` where `j > 0`.
                //   Moving from `j > 0` to `0` is `j > i`, which is free.
                //   This logic is wrong. The example output is 3.
                //
                // The problem states: decrement `a_i`, increment `a_j`.
                // If `a_i` is positive, we need to decrement it `a_i` times.
                // If `a_i` is negative, we need to increment it `|a_i|` times.
                //
                // Let's consider the net flow.
                // We iterate from left to right.
                // `current_balance` = sum of `a_k` for `k < i`.
                // When we are at `a_i`:
                // If `a_i > 0`: We have `a_i` units to move out.
                //   These `a_i` units can be used to satisfy previous deficits (if `current_balance < 0`).
                //   Or they can be added to `current_balance` to be moved to the right.
                // If `a_i < 0`: We need `|a_i|` units.
                //   These `|a_i|` units can be taken from `current_balance` (if `current_balance > 0`).
                //   Or they must come from the right (if `current_balance <= 0`).
                //
                // Let `current_balance` be the sum of `a_1, ..., a_i`.
                // If `current_balance` is positive, it means we have `current_balance` units that have been "passed through" or generated up to `i`.
                // These units are available to be moved to `j > i`. This is free.
                // If `current_balance` is negative, it means we have a deficit of `|current_balance|` units up to `i`.
                // These units must be supplied from `j > i`. This is also free (move from `j` to `i`, `j > i`).
                //
                // The only way to incur cost is to move a unit from `i` to `j` where `i > j`.
                // This means we had an excess at `i` (or some `k > j` that contributed to `i`'s excess)
                // and we used it to satisfy a deficit at `j` (or some `k < i` that contributed to `j`'s deficit).
                //
                // This implies that any time we have a positive `a_i` and we use it to satisfy a negative `a_j` where `j < i`, it costs.
                //
                // Let's maintain `free_money`: the amount of positive value that has accumulated from `a_k` where `k < current_index`,
                // and has not yet been used to satisfy any `a_j < current_index` that was negative.
                //
                // Iterate `i` from `0` to `n-1`.
                // `val = a[i]`.
                // If `val > 0`:
                //   Add `val` to `free_money`. These are units that can be moved to `j > i` for free.
                // If `val < 0`:
                //   We need `|val|` units.
                //   Try to satisfy this need from `free_money`.
                //   `take = min(free_money, |val|)`.
                //   `free_money -= take`.
                //   `remaining_need = |val| - take`.
                //   If `remaining_need > 0`:
                //     These `remaining_need` units must come from `a_j` where `j > i`.
                //     Moving from `j > i` to `i` is free.
                //     So, this doesn't incur cost.
                //
                // This logic still gives 0 cost for the first example.
                // `a = [-3, 5, -3, 1]`
                // `i=0, a_0 = -3`. `free_money = 0`. `val = -3`.
                //   `take = min(0, 3) = 0`. `free_money = 0`. `remaining_need = 3`.
                //   No cost.
                // `i=1, a_1 = 5`. `val = 5`.
                //   `free_money += 5`. `free_money = 5`.
                // `i=2, a_2 = -3`. `val = -3`.
                //   `take = min(5, 3) = 3`. `free_money = 5 - 3 = 2`. `remaining_need = 0`.
                //   No cost.
                // `i=3, a_3 = 1`. `val = 1`.
                //   `free_money += 1`. `free_money = 3`.
                // Final cost = 0. Example output = 3.
                //
                // The interpretation of "free" and "costly" operations must be key.
                // "decrement `a_i` by one and increment `a_j` by one."
                // This means we are moving a unit of value from `i` to `j`.
                // If `i < j`, free. (Move right)
                // If `i > j`, cost 1. (Move left)
                //
                // We want to make all `a_k = 0`.
                // This means for every `a_k > 0`, we must move `a_k` units out of `k`.
                // For every `a_k < 0`, we must move `|a_k|` units into `k`.
                //
                // The total sum of `a_k` is 0.
                // Let `P_sum = sum(a_k for a_k > 0)`.
                // Let `N_sum = sum(a_k for a_k < 0)`.
                // `P_sum + N_sum = 0`, so `P_sum = -N_sum`.
                //
                // We need to move `P_sum` units out of positive positions.
                // We need to move `P_sum` units into negative positions.
                //
                // Consider the prefix sum `S_k = a_1 + ... + a_k`.
                // If `S_k` becomes negative, say `S_k = -X`.
                // This means that `a_1, ..., a_k` collectively need `X` units.
                // These `X` units must come from `a_j` where `j > k`.
                // Moving from `j > k` to `i <= k` is a move from `j` to `i` where `j > i`. This is free.
                // So, if `S_k` becomes negative, it doesn't directly incur cost.
                //
                // If `S_k` becomes positive, say `S_k = Y`.
                // This means that `a_1, ..., a_k` collectively have an excess of `Y` units.
                // These `Y` units must be moved to `a_j` where `j > k`.
                // Moving from `i <= k` to `j > k` is a move from `i` to `j` where `i < j`. This is free.
                // So, if `S_k` becomes positive, it doesn't directly incur cost.
                //
                // This is still leading to 0 cost.
                //
                // The problem is about *net* flow.
                // Let's consider the state as `current_balance`.
                // `current_balance` is the sum of `a_i` processed so far.
                //
                // `a = [-3, 5, -3, 1]`
                // `i=0, a_0 = -3`. `current_balance = -3`.
                //   We need 3 units. These must come from `j > 0`. This is free.
                // `i=1, a_1 = 5`. `current_balance = -3 + 5 = 2`.
                //   We have 2 excess units. These must go to `j > 1`. This is free.
                // `i=2, a_2 = -3`. `current_balance = 2 - 3 = -1`.
                //   We need 1 unit. This must come from `j > 2`. This is free.
                // `i=3, a_3 = 1`. `current_balance = -1 + 1 = 0`.
                //   We have 0 excess/deficit.
                //
                // This is the standard prefix sum argument for minimum operations if all moves are free.
                // The cost comes from `i > j`.
                //
                // What if we have `a_i > 0` and `a_j < 0` with `i > j`?
                // We want to move `a_i` units from `i` to `j`. This costs 1 per unit.
                //
                // Let's track `current_positive_sum`. This is the sum of `a_k > 0` for `k <= i` that have not yet been "cancelled out" by `a_j < 0` for `j <= i`.
                //
                // `a = [-3, 5, -3, 1]`
                // `cost = 0`. `current_positive_sum = 0`.
                //
                // `i=0, a_0 = -3`.
                //   We need 3 units.
                //   `current_positive_sum` is 0. We don't have any positive values from left.
                //   So, these 3 units must come from `j > 0`.
                //   Moving from `j > 0` to `0` is free.
                //   This `a_0` is satisfied by future elements.
                //   `current_positive_sum` remains 0.
                //
                // `i=1, a_1 = 5`.
                //   We have 5 units.
                //   These 5 units are available to satisfy future negative values (`j > 1`) for free.
                //   Or they could satisfy past negative values (`j < 1`) for cost.
                //   The problem is to minimize cost. So we prefer free moves.
                //   So, we add 5 to `current_positive_sum`. `current_positive_sum = 5`.
                //
                // `i=2, a_2 = -3`.
                //   We need 3 units.
                //   We have `current_positive_sum = 5`.
                //   We can take 3 units from `current_positive_sum`. This is a move from `k < 2` to `2`.
                //   This is `k < i`, so it's free.
                //   `current_positive_sum = 5 - 3 = 2`.
                //
                // `i=3, a_3 = 1`.
                //   We have 1 unit.
                //   Add to `current_positive_sum`. `current_positive_sum = 2 + 1 = 3`.
                //
                // Final `cost = 0`. Still wrong.
                //
                // The example explanation:
                // Do `(i=2, j=3)` three times (free), `a = [-3, 2, 0, 1]`.
                //   This means `a_2` (original index 1, value 5) is decremented, `a_3` (original index 2, value -3) is incremented.
                //   This is `a_1` (value 5) and `a_2` (value -3).
                //   `a_1` is decremented, `a_2` is incremented. `i=1, j=2`. `i < j`, free.
                //   This is `a_1` (value 5) and `a_2` (value -3).
                //   `a_1` becomes `5-3=2`. `a_2` becomes `-3+3=0`.
                //   Array becomes `[-3, 2, 0, 1]`.
                //
                // Do `(i=2, j=1)` two times (pay two coins), `a = [-1, 0, 0, 1]`.
                //   This means `a_2` (original index 1, value 2) is decremented, `a_1` (original index 0, value -3) is incremented.
                //   This is `a_1` (value 2) and `a_0` (value -3).
                //   `a_1` is decremented, `a_0` is incremented. `i=1, j=0`. `i > j`, cost 1.
                //   This happens 2 times. Cost = 2.
                //   `a_1` becomes `2-2=0`. `a_0` becomes `-3+2=-1`.
                //   Array becomes `[-1, 0, 0, 1]`.
                //
                // Do `(i=4, j=1)` one time (pay one coin), `a = [0, 0, 0, 0]`.
                //   This means `a_4` (original index 3, value 1) is decremented, `a_1` (original index 0, value -1) is incremented.
                //   This is `a_3` (value 1) and `a_0` (value -1).
                //   `a_3` is decremented, `a_0` is incremented. `i=3, j=0`. `i > j`, cost 1.
                //   This happens 1 time. Cost = 1.
                //   `a_3` becomes `1-1=0`. `a_0` becomes `-1+1=0`.
                //   Array becomes `[0, 0, 0, 0]`.
